
The 32-ton howitzer lifted its long barrel skyward, froze momentarily, then shook the earth with a chest-pounding roar. Over the next few hours, five of the armored artillery pieces repeatedly blasted a rocky hillside posing as a mock terrorist hideout nearly five miles away. Mortars and an Air Force jet joined in the firestorm. "Boy, you can feel that all the way down in your heart," said Sgt. 1st Class Ronnie Perryman of Millen as nearby soldiers of the Georgia Army National Guard cheered and snapped photos with digital cameras. 

